    {
      "title": "إِنَّ and Its Sisters",
      "titleArabic": "إِنَّ وَأَخَوَاتُهَا",
      "content": [
        "إِنَّ and its 'sisters' are particles that enter upon nominal sentences for emphasis or specific meanings. They change the subject (اسم إِنَّ) to accusative case, while the predicate (خبر إِنَّ) remains nominative.",
        "The main sisters are: إِنَّ (indeed), أَنَّ (that), لَكِنَّ (but), كَأَنَّ (as if), لَيْتَ (I wish), and لَعَلَّ (perhaps)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "إِنَّ (indeed) - for emphasis: إِنَّ الطَّالِبَ مُجْتَهِدٌ",
        "أَنَّ (that) - in subordinate clauses",
        "لَكِنَّ (but) - for contrast",
        "Subject after إِنَّ takes fatha (accusative)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "إِنَّ الْكِتَابَ جَدِيدٌ", "english": "Indeed, the book is new" },
        { "arabic": "إِنَّ الطَّالِبَ مُجْتَهِدٌ", "english": "Indeed, the student is diligent" },
        { "arabic": "الْبَيْتُ صَغِيرٌ لَكِنَّ الْغُرْفَةَ كَبِيرَةٌ", "english": "The house is small but the room is big" },
        { "arabic": "عَلِمْتُ أَنَّ الْمُدَرِّسَ حَاضِرٌ", "english": "I knew that the teacher is present" }
      ]
    }
  ],
